“EchoBloom: A bio-acoustic, shape-memory alloy ‘bloom’ for monitoring and interacting with marine life. Imagine a shimmering, bioluminescent, jellyfish-like device, roughly the size of a large grapefruit. Embedded within its gelatinous structure are thousands of microscopic shape-memory alloy filaments – reacting to both sound and water pressure – creating a dynamic, responsive interface for observing and subtly influencing marine animal behavior. It transmits bio-acoustic data (sonar and dolphin-like clicks) *and* visual patterns via bioluminescence, creating a mesmerizing, three-dimensional representation of the underwater environment. Crucially, users can modulate the sonic output – broadcasting calming frequencies to reduce anxiety in stressed marine mammals, or even subtle ‘calls’ to guide them towards specific locations for research or conservation. The shape-memory alloy filaments actively *respond* to the marine life's movements, essentially creating a dynamic, interactive shadow puppet show of the ocean. It even has a ‘self-healing’ capability if bumped into by a particularly enthusiastic sea turtle!”